-{"id":"bd-j9jo3","title":"robot-redesign: operator-centric robot mode overhaul","description":"Overhaul ntm robot mode around an operator-centric, SQLite-backed projection model that makes snapshot, events, digest, attention, status, REST, and dashboard surfaces converge on one coherent contract. This work exists to replace command-local state assembly with a restart-safe, self-describing, agent-ergonomic system while explicitly preserving ntm's tmux-first mission and rejecting DuckDB or a fleet-analytics-first architecture.","design":"This epic is the umbrella for the full robot-mode redesign. The target architecture has a shared normalized projection layer in Go, persisted derived state in SQLite, a persistent attention journal with replay-safe cursors, durable incidents for sticky operator pain, checked-in schema artifacts, and parity across CLI/REST/dashboard renderers.\n\nNon-negotiables:\n- SQLite only; do not introduce DuckDB or a second analytical store.\n- snapshot is the canonical bootstrap surface; do not create a redundant overview command unless later evidence proves snapshot cannot carry that responsibility.\n- status becomes a cheap summary surface, not a second bootstrap dump.\n- attention, digest, and events are the canonical delta/tending loop.\n- source freshness and degradation are first-class contract elements.\n- ntm remains tmux-first and project/session-centric, not a generic fleet cockpit.\n\nThe graph below intentionally separates hierarchy from blocking edges: epics group work, while explicit dependencies encode execution order. That keeps the bead graph readable and prevents epic containers from accidentally becoming the only blockers future implementation agents can see.","acceptance_criteria":"The bead graph is complete when all child epics and tasks required for: contract definition, SQLite schema/store work, source adapters, persistent attention replay, incidents, robot surface rewrites, registry/capabilities updates, parity work, testing, docs, and legacy cleanup are represented and wired with meaningful dependencies.\n\nA successful implementation of this epic yields one coherent operator loop and a robot contract that future agents can understand without consulting an external planning document.","notes":"Success should be judged by operator ergonomics and contract discipline, not by raw command count. If a proposed implementation adds more robot flags without reducing ambiguity or duplication, it is moving in the wrong direction.\n\nFuture implementers should treat this epic as the strategic guardrail: the goal is fewer stronger surfaces, better shared data, better restart safety, and clearer degraded-state semantics.","status":"open","priority":4,"issue_type":"epic","estimated_minutes":480,"created_at":"2026-03-21T23:32:03.012585289Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-22T00:10:20.156686303Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["robot-redesign"],"comments":[{"id":312,"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3","author":"ubuntu","text":"Why this exists: ntm already has strong pieces, especially the attention-feed direction, but the current robot surfaces still overlap and are assembled too locally. This epic captures the decision to finish that architecture properly instead of accreting more one-off commands and partial state views.","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:32:03Z"},{"id":328,"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3","author":"ubuntu","text":"Execution order embedded in the graph: contracts -> SQLite/runtime projection -> adapters/source health -> durable attention/cursors -> incidents -> surface rewrites -> registry/discovery -> REST/dashboard/streaming parity -> validation/docs/cleanup.\n\nArchitectural intent to preserve: SQLite only; no DuckDB; snapshot is the bootstrap surface; status stays cheap; digest+attention are the ongoing operator loop; inspect surfaces answer focused follow-up questions; all transports project from the same shared runtime model; incidents capture recurring operator pain; schema IDs and freshness/degraded metadata are first-class contract elements.\n\nNon-goals that should remain visible to future implementers: do not recreate command sprawl, do not add an overview sibling just because snapshot is weak, do not let renderers or transports invent separate semantics, and do not keep legacy assembly paths alive once the shared model is authoritative.","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:40:25Z"}]}
