 {"id":"bd-j9jo3.1","title":"robot-redesign/contracts: end-state contract and surface taxonomy","description":"Define the authoritative end-state robot contract before implementation work begins so the rest of the graph has stable surface responsibilities, data boundaries, and non-goals. This epic exists to stop robot mode from growing by accretion and to ensure every later task can point back to a crisp contract instead of vague intent.","design":"The contract layer answers four questions: which surfaces exist, what each surface owns, what normalized sections they share, and how schema/freshness/degraded-state metadata travel with every major response. This is the place where we explicitly lock in that snapshot owns bootstrap, status is cheap summary, and attention/digest/events own the tending loop.\n\nThis epic also captures the choice to make projection sections, schema identifiers, and degraded-source semantics first-class concepts instead of implementation details buried in individual commands.","acceptance_criteria":"This epic is complete when later implementers can derive SQLite schema, source adapters, event persistence, and output renderers from a single coherent contract description rather than improvising per-command behavior.","notes":"Contract work is foundational because changing it late would churn every downstream surface, test, and parity layer. Any ambiguity left here will multiply in the rest of the graph.","status":"closed","priority":4,"issue_type":"epic","estimated_minutes":240,"created_at":"2026-03-21T23:32:04.047577022Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-26T19:52:27.408989087Z","closed_at":"2026-03-26T19:52:27.408673927Z","close_reason":"All contract child beads bd-j9jo3.1.1 through bd-j9jo3.1.15 are closed; leaving the epic open was creating triage noise, not preserving real remaining work.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["contracts","robot-redesign"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:32:04.047577022Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":313,"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1","author":"ubuntu","text":"Future self: if implementation pressure tempts you to skip this and start coding surfaces directly, don't. The whole purpose of this redesign is to eliminate hidden overlap and implicit semantics.","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:32:04Z"}]}
 {"id":"bd-j9jo3.1.1","title":"robot-redesign/contracts: define robot surface taxonomy and lane responsibilities","description":"Write the authoritative taxonomy for robot surfaces so future implementation work stops adding overlapping commands with implicit responsibilities. This task defines which surfaces own bootstrap, summary, delta replay, prioritization, drill-down inspection, and actuation.","design":"The output of this bead should explicitly map ntm's operator loop into named lanes: bootstrap, summarize, replay, triage, inspect, and act. It should explain why snapshot owns bootstrap, why status must stay cheap, why events/digest/attention own the tending loop, and why actuation should continue to flow through explicit existing commands instead of hidden planner behavior.\n\nThis task must also identify non-goals, especially: no DuckDB, no fleet-first worldview, no reflexive new overview command, and no further growth of ambiguous command-local state dumps.","acceptance_criteria":"Produce a self-contained taxonomy that names each robot surface, states its job, states what it must not do, and explains how the surfaces fit together into the canonical operator loop.\n\nThe result should be clear enough that downstream tasks can cite it instead of restating intent.","notes":"Treat this task as the place where command sprawl stops. If a later surface cannot be justified against this taxonomy, it should probably be a section or mode of an existing surface instead.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","estimated_minutes":180,"created_at":"2026-03-21T23:34:16.746441323Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-22T03:23:59.289076573Z","closed_at":"2026-03-22T03:23:59.287962877Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["contracts","robot-redesign","surfaces"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.1","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:34:16.746441323Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":322,"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.1","author":"ubuntu","text":"This is the first anti-entropy task in the graph. Future implementation quality will be strongly correlated with how crisp this taxonomy is.","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:34:17Z"}]}
 {"id":"bd-j9jo3.1.10","title":"robot-redesign/contracts: define request identity, idempotency, retry, and correlation semantics","description":"Define how robot actuation and operator-loop requests are identified, correlated, retried, and deduplicated so machine consumers can safely repeat work without causing duplicate side effects or losing track of which outcome belongs to which request. This task exists because stable target refs solve what to act on, but the redesign still lacks an explicit contract for how clients identify the act itself across retries, reconnects, transport switches, and delayed verification.","design":"The contract should define request IDs or correlation IDs, optional idempotency keys or retry tokens, their scope and lifetime, how they appear in command responses and later outcome or diagnostic payloads, what makes a retry safe versus unsafe, and how duplicate, superseded, or conflicting requests are reported. It should explain how control commands, digest/attention outcome events, inspect diagnostics, REST, CLI, SSE, and WebSocket all surface the same request-correlation story, including what clients can persist locally to recover from transport failure or ambiguous timeout without reintroducing duplicate work.\n\nThe goal is not to bolt on distributed-systems ceremony. The goal is to make operator retries, reconciliation, and follow-up inspection trustworthy enough that agents do not create accidental duplicate work or misattribute results.","acceptance_criteria":"Produce a self-contained request identity and idempotency contract that downstream actuation-outcome, surface, registry, parity, docs, and validation tasks can implement directly.\n\nThe result must make it obvious how a consumer safely retries after timeout or disconnect, how a later outcome is correlated back to the originating request, and how duplicate, superseded, or ambiguous requests are surfaced.","notes":"If an agent still has to guess whether reissuing a command is safe or whether a later outcome belongs to its own prior request, this task is incomplete.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","estimated_minutes":180,"created_at":"2026-03-22T00:22:22.405544219Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-22T16:42:36.056684362Z","closed_at":"2026-03-22T16:42:36.056224842Z","close_reason":"Verified implemented in robot-request-identity.md (609 lines). Contract covers: request_id structure (req_timestamp_random), idempotency_key for dedup, correlation_id for linking requests, parent_request_id for chains. Retry semantics: safe vs unsafe retries, duplicate detection with duplicate field and original_response. Transport consistency across CLI, REST, WebSocket. Outcome correlation and timeout handling. Full acceptance criteria coverage.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["contracts","ergonomics","idempotency","robot-redesign"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.10","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:22:22.405544219Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.10","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:23:28.362840127Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.10","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.2","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:23:28.925188567Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.10","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.7","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:23:29.510015557Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.10","depends_on_id":"bd-j9jo3.1.9","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:23:30.079773721Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
